Biodiversity 10.1002/cbdv.202000057 Link to VoR: http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/cbdv.202000057 Associated Streptomyces and Stereochemical Revision of Julichromes Q3·5 and Q3·3 Chunyao Ling, Zhenbin Zhou, Zhiyun Chen, Xuehong Chen, and Jianhua Ju anthraquinones  [chrysophanol  (8),  4-acetylchrysophanol  (9),  islandicin  (10),  huanglongmycin  A  (11)],  were  isolated  from  the  marine  gastropod  mollusk  Batillaria zonalis-associated Streptomyces sampsonii SCSIO 054. This is the first report of julichromes isolated from a marine source. Extensive dissection  of 1D and 2D NMR datasets combined with X-ray crystallography enabled rigorous elucidation of the previously reported configurations of julichrome Q3·5  (4) and related julichrome Q3·3 (5); both of the stereochemistry at C(9) needs to be revised. In addition, julichrome Q12 (2) was found to display antibacterial

activity against Micrococcus luteus and Bacillus subtilis with MICs of 2.0 and 8.0 μg mL-1; compounds 1, 3, 6 and 7 also showed inhibitory activities against  an array of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus, S. aureus and S. simulans AKA1 with MIC values ranging from 8 to 64 μg mL-1.  Keywords: julichromes, absolute configuration, structure revision, antibacterial activity shiodaensi.[1]  Julimycin  B-II,  the  first  derivative  of  a  typical  β,  β’-bianthraquinonyl  species,  displays  anti-viral  and  anti-polio  activities.  The  structure of julimycin B-II was originally elucidated by means of spectroscopic and chemical methods but no direct X-ray crystallographic data.[2, 3]  To date, over 20 natural julichromes have been reported and these can all be classified as either dimeric or monomeric although the vast majority  exist  as  dimers.  Julichrome  compounds  display  a  wide  array  of  biological  activities  including,  but  not  limited  to  antimicrobial,  antitumor,  antioxidant and anti-phytodevelopmental activities.[4-6] Key to the biosynthesis of the julichromes is a cytochrome P450 monooxygenase that carries  out  a  regioselective  intermolecular  oxidative  phenol-coupling  reaction  manner  to  install  a  unique  biaryl  linkage  characteristic  of  the  dimeric  julichromes.[7]  The  monomer julichrome  Q6, derived  from a common nonaketide precursor, serves  a vital  role  in  the production  of  many  dimer- based julichromes by virtue of its use as a monomer.   capabilities  to  ward  off  potential  predators  or  by  endowing  the  host  competitive  advantages  over  other  competing  organisms.[8]  Relatedly,

actinomycetes  from  marine-derived  microorganisms  are  now  well-established  as  producers  of  clinically  important  anti-infective  and  antitumor  agents.  In  the  past  decade,  our  research  group  has  focused  on  the  discovery  of  bioactive  metabolites  from  marine-derived  actinomycetes  endogenous  to  the  South  China  Sea.[9-10]  Of  particular  interest,  Batillaria  zonalis  is  a  common  snail  that  inhabits  intertidal  zones.  A  microbial  symbiont, B. zonalis is closely associated with Streptomyces sampsonii SCSIO 054; presumably the Batillaria serves as a host for SCSIO 054. Not  surprisingly, products of this symbiotic relationship have been found to display strong activity against Gram-positive bacteria. We report here that,  as envisioned, S. sampsonii SCSIO 054 produces two new julichrome monomers (1, 2) together with five known julichromes [ Q10 (3), Q3·5 (4), Q3·3  (5), Q6·6 (6), Q6 (7)] and four known anthraquinones [chrysophanol (8), 4-acetylchrysophanol (9), islandicin (10), huanglongmycin A (11)]. This  marks the first time that julichromes have been isolated from a marine source. Additionally, careful analyses of HRESIMS, NMR (both 1D and 2D  data),  combined  with  X-ray  single  crystal  diffraction  analyses,  reveal  that  the  previously  reported  stereochemical  configurations  at  C-9  of  julichrome  Q3·5  (4)  and  julichrome  Q3·3  (5)  require  revision. Important to realize is that compound 4 assumes two preferred conformations, 4a (P) and 4b (M) (Figure 4), due to free rotation  about the biaryl C7-C7’ bond. To detect the presence of axial chirality, chiral HPLC analysis was carried out on 4; chromatographic optimization  efforts only ever enabled the observance of one independent peak representative of 4. Our inability to resolve the different putative conformers of 4  was  in  good  accordance  with  calculated  potential  energy  scans  of  dihedral  C1’-C2’-C-C2-C1.  These  calculations  had  indicated  that  the  energy  barriers of the two transition states lie below than minimum free energy barrier (93.5KJ/mol, 300 K).[19] The combination of these theoretical and  observed data thus established that compound 4 is not an atropisomer.  with previously reported data.[7] Because the absolute configuration of co-isolated julichrome Q3·5 (4) was confirmed by X-ray crystallography, the

Other compounds 1, 3, 6 and 7 also showed inhibitory activities against an array of methicillin-resistant S. aureus, S. aureus and S.  simulans  AKA1  with  MIC  values  of  8–64  μg  mL-1.  In  contrast,  compounds  4,  5  and  7–11  failed  to  show  notable  antibacterial  activities.  These  results reveal that the julichrome containing naphthalene ring fusion with the cyclohexanone scaffold enhances antibacterial activities and that of  anthraquinone-type scaffold abolishes antimicrobial activities.  from Batillaria zonalis-associated S. sampsonii SCSIO 054. X-ray crystallographic analysis of 4 revealed its absolute stereochemical configuration  and  facilitated  the  revision  of  absolute  configuration  from  9R  to  9S  in  the  julichrome  family.  Compounds  1–3,  6  and  7  displayed  antimicrobial  activities  against  M.  luteus,  B.  subtilis,  MRSA  669,  MRSA  991,  MRSA  1862,  MRSA  GDE4P037P,  S.  aureus  ATCC  29213,  S.  aureus  (cfr)  GDQ6P012P and S. simulans AKA1 with MIC values ranging from 2–64 μg mL-1. Structure-activity relationship analyses reveal that ring-unsaturated  julichrome displays better antimicrobial activities comparison with anthraquinone-type polyketides. The moderate degrees of biological activity noted for  members of the julichrome family suggest that their producer, SCSIO 054, likely plays an important symbiotic role in enabling its B. zonalis host to  defend itself from assorted predators. This putative symbiont system, combined with the results generated here, strongly suggest that 1–3, 6 and 7  may constitute excellent antimicrobial drug leads. Additionally, the two new monomers identified here provide new insights into the biosynthetic  origins of the julichrome family members.
